	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU agrees new rules of origin</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The European Commission has issued a Regulation introducing new rules of origin (RoO) that will affect directly the exports of all non-EPA states and influence the continuing negotiations within interim EPAs. The regulation, which marks a milestone in a process launched in 2003, sets out the EU’s intentions with respect to RoO and amends some clauses of the current provisions to give effect to these. Clear preference is given to LDCs.</p><p>The changes apply only to the Generalised System of Preferences (GSP) which, being an autonomous EU policy, can be amended without any negotiation with trade partners. Since all ACP states that have not initialled or signed EPAs now trade with the EU under the GSP, the new rules will apply directly to their exports with immediate effect. EPA countries will be affected only when negotiating new RoO (as foreseen in all the interim agreements), since the EU position is likely to reflect the new policy.</p><p>There are many, complex changes set out in the regulation, which will need to be studied very carefully in relation to the changes for specific exports. But four broad changes may have an immediate importance for non-EPA states:</p>
<ul>

<li>The first applies only to LDCs and mirrors the EPA innovation on clothing, requiring only a single transformation of non-originating inputs. This will allow, for example, an LDC to import non-originating Asian cloth, transform it into garments and export them duty free to the EU. Whilst this may help ACP clothing industries, it could weaken their demand for originating cotton. </li>

<li>The second change is to move forward a switch to value-added as the normal criterion for establishing whether an exporter has undertaken ‘sufficient processing’. The current rules apply a mix of criteria – some relating to the tariff code of inputs, some to the processes that must be undertaken, and some to the share of value that must be added. However, the new emphasis on value-added will not apply to all sectors – and none of the proposed new rules for agricultural products (in HS chapters 1-24) includes a value-added option (though many set a maximum weight for non-originating inputs). Originating status for fish also remains determined by the nationality of the fishing boat, but the rules have been made less hard to achieve. In those sectors that do have a value-added criterion (which is normally an alternative to the existing rules rather than a replacement), the rule for LDCs is often less onerous than for other developing countries. </li>

<li>The third relates to ‘cumulation’ (in which two or more states contribute to achieving ‘sufficient processing’). The new regulation makes this easier to achieve for GSP beneficiaries, but only between countries with identical RoO, i.e. not between LDCs and other developing countries on clothing, or in any other case where the former face lower value-added requirements than the latter. Hence, it will not necessarily allow non-EPA ACP states to cumulate as they could under Cotonou.</li>

<li>The fourth change proposes to shift responsibility for applying and monitoring the RoO system from the customs department of the exporting countries to the private-sector exporting firms through a system of approved exporters. Obligatory implementation of this change is deferred to 2017. </li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
European Commission, ‘Commission Regulation (EU) No 1063/2010 concerning the GSP rules of origin (+ impact assessment)’, 18 November 2010<br />
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id=5496&amp;doc_language=Both" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/library_detail.php?library_detail_id...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>From an economist viewpoint, there is much to be said in using value-added as the measure of whether or not sufficient working has been done in a country to confer originating status. But the big question is the level at which the threshold is set. In the new rules it is often set at 30% for LDCs and 50% for others. This far exceeds the levels of value-added that stimulate intra-industry trade between firms in cases where there are no preferences to consider - simply a commercial decision whether or not to ship out some parts of processing to a foreign country. Whilst the typical value-added in commercial transactions unrelated to preferences varies by product (with a wide range within each sector),value-added of less than 10% is quite sufficient in some sectors to justify some processes to be done abroad, whilst value-added of under 25% is very common. Exporters (including those of processed agricultural goods that do not fall in Chapters 1-24) will need to study the new rules carefully to determine whether they are easier or harder to fulfil than the existing ones. And agricultural exporters will need to exercise similar care scrutinising the rules on the maximum share of export weight contributed by non-originating inputs.</p><p>On cumulation, a major problem (applying equally to the EPA rules) is that there must exist a formal agreement between the customs authorities of each and every cumulating pair of states (and between them and the EU) before any cumulation is allowed. This may make it hard for agricultural exporters in one state to have their goods processed in another without losing preferences.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
